  "title": "Agile Governance Structure",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "30727a3f9dd24668",
      "text": "With governance, as with other aspects, we should apply the same bootstrapping philosophy we use with building currency and software in general. Explicitly that means working on software implementation, interface design, and (soft) process in small agile increments."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "63fc87b7a2c4f76c",
      "text": "As with the currency stuff there will probably be a split between a group that wants to take things slowly slowly and build through soft consensus and a lot of meetings - and those that want more structure fast and concentrate on making with less talk. Those that like neither (probably the best of us) will drop out of both and remain islands."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1719c10477eb8adc",
      "text": "The former is the only tried and tested technique for community and informal group meeting. It works. Consensus building through a lot of meetings - either using online tools like [[Loomio]] or more commonly through cooperative governance processes as tried in various places around the world."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "27c5c59cca3bcad1",
      "text": "The latter is untested and new - or rather it has been tested in my circles a few times over the last 20 years and never worked."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a647b48c60086cdb",
      "text": "It is an agile approach which marries the tool development, with the legal structures and the community development in fast rapid development cycles."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6065558a78c7306d",
      "text": "It has a far greater emphasis on making, and places firm but flexible restrictions on \"conversations\" - those are to be held outside of regular meetings for instance, and formally structured into weekend events that take place once every month or three months depending on the development cycle."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bd702064e4298b53",
      "text": "To get concrete this means the following sort of differences of approach:\n1. The second and tested approach (let's call it \"community building\") is to slowly add structure to this group and look to debating and forming a legal structure say in 3-6 months time based on a constitution agreed through consensus. That document then stays on the shelf.\n1. The first approach is to quickly get up a legal structure using available tools such as OneClickOrgs - based simply and minimally on one member one vote. We then build for instance a quick VSM interface for our sustainable governance by sketching the various functions 1-3, 4, and 5 and quickly tie that to working code associated with out governance. We bring on people who actually want to build and use this structure, and avoid long conversations with people who are not already on bord with the core mission to build and use themselves the prototype.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ce44ee94b0105d88",
      "text": "This second approach was not possible and failed before in the several experiments I have seen and been part of because:\n- The software was not available to support the structure - so groups tried it for many many months without any tools they could actually use and put no other processes in place they could use to make decisions in the mean time - [http://www.jofreeman.com/joreen/tyranny.htm jofreeman.com]\n- There was not general awareness of these issues - currencies and governance in the social sphere or software sphere. Governance was a dirty word in both sectors - at least in daily practice.\n- There was no possibility of financing such initiatives\nAs a result attempts at 2 universally failed due to classic \"Tyranny of Structurelessness\" issues and the fact that no money ever came into to avoid the inevitable burn out."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9c6567aec3d920d1",
      "text": "The only successful project therefore either quickly adopted conventional legal structures in order to obtain finance, or went down the consensus path best exemplified by Enspiral in New Zealand - [https://enspiral.com/ enspiral.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b91dcaf311ba26cc",
      "text": "More people working on stuff that matters Powerful things take place when like minded people connect. Network Overview Get to know the bigger picture Our Ventures Working together for positive change\nThe hope and aim of many social blockchain projects is to come up with new structures of governance of these things that offer the ability to scale in more frictionless ways than Enspiral offers, is more agile, but does not trash the human and social aspects like conventional hierarchical company structures do."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6f34cb754942717e",
      "text": "My proposal is that Platform Earth's core mission in terms of product and services is to provide a new and compelling model of governance which we need to apply for instance to Voz and the ecommony currency model."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "593c8336db4523dd",
      "text": "just as with the software development of the currency we need to test out and refine our own governance process and iteratively encode that into the software and services and documentation of our product.\nIt is for these reasons that I reject the consensual approach to governance - and instead recommend an agile approach to building governance software which we ourselves use.\nThe softer community building aspect should not be discarded however - it is a tried and tested way of building awareness and teamwork around a movement.\nBut this layer should be outside of the membrane - it should be an on-boarding process and learning space which is in continual dialogue with system 4.\nPeople who do not have the time, commitment or fully agree with what is being built are encouraged to take part in the wider more informal community - or even start a forked version of a product. But the process of managing making something, and the team formation that entails must happen within the membrane, and it should be using the tools it is advocating others to use.\n\nFor the first time in history - that looks a feasible project."
    }
